defs.docs:
Amethyst is a free and open source game engine written in idiomatic
 [Rust][rs] for building video games and interactive multimedia applications.
 The source code is available for download on [GitHub][gh]. See the
 [online book][bk] for a complete guide to using Amethyst.

defs.name: Result
defs.docs: Convenience alias for use in main functions that uses Amethyst.

defs.name: prelude
defs.docs: Contains common types that can be glob-imported (`*`) for convenience.

defs.name: CoreApplication
defs.docs:
`CoreApplication` is the application implementation for the game engine. This is fully generic
 over the state type and event type.

defs.name: Application
defs.docs:
An Application is the root object of the game engine. It binds the OS
 event loop, state machines, timers and other core components in a central place.

defs.name: new
defs.value: fn <P, S, I> (path: P, initial_state: S, init: I) -> Result<Self, Error>
defs.docs:
Creates a new Application with the given initial game state.
 This will create and allocate all the needed resources for
 the event loop of the game engine. It is a shortcut for convenience
 if you need more control over how the engine is configured you should
 be using [build](struct.Application.html#method.build) instead.

defs.name: build
defs.value: fn <P, S> (path: P, initial_state: S) -> Result<ApplicationBuilder<S, T, E, R>, Error>
defs.docs: Creates a new ApplicationBuilder with the given initial game state.

defs.name: run
defs.docs:
Run the gameloop until the game state indicates that the game is no
 longer running. This is done via the `State` returning `Trans::Quit` or
 `Trans::Pop` on the last state in from the stack. See full
 documentation on this in [State](trait.State.html) documentation.

defs.name: ApplicationBuilder
defs.docs:
`ApplicationBuilder` is an interface that allows for creation of an
 [`Application`](struct.Application.html)
 using a custom set of configuration. This is the normal way an
 [`Application`](struct.Application.html)
 object is created.

fn

(path: P, initial_state: S) -> Result
defs.docs:
Creates a new [ApplicationBuilder](struct.ApplicationBuilder.html) instance

defs.name: register
defs.docs:
Registers a component into the entity-component-system. This method
 takes no options other than the component type which is defined
 using a 'turbofish'. See the example for what this looks like.

defs.name: ignore_window_close

Tells the resulting application window to ignore close events if ignore is true.
 This will make your game window unresponsive to operating system close commands.
 Use with caution.

defs.name: Trans
defs.docs:
Types of state transitions.
 T is the type of shared data between states.
 E is the type of events

defs.name: TransEvent
defs.value: Box<dyn Fn() -> Trans<T, E> + Send + Sync + 'static>
defs.docs:
Event queue to trigger state `Trans` from other places than a `State`'s methods.
 # Example:
 ```rust, ignore
 world.write_resource::<EventChannel<TransEvent<MyGameData, StateEvent>>>().single_write(Box::new(|| Trans::Quit));
 ```

defs.name: EmptyTrans
defs.docs: An empty `Trans`. Made to be used with `EmptyState`.

defs.name: SimpleTrans
defs.docs:
A simple default `Trans`. Made to be used with `SimpleState`.
 By default it contains a `GameData` as its `StateData` and doesn't have a custom event type.

defs.docs: Executed when the game state begins.

defs.name: on_stop
defs.docs: Executed when the game state exits.

defs.name: on_pause
defs.docs: Executed when a different game state is pushed onto the stack.

defs.name: on_resume
defs.docs: Executed when the application returns to this game state once again.

defs.name: handle_event
defs.value: fn (&mut self, _data: StateData<'_, T>, _event: E) -> Trans<T, E>

defs.name: fixed_update
defs.value: fn (&mut self, _data: StateData<'_, T>) -> Trans<T, E>
defs.docs:
Executed repeatedly at stable, predictable intervals (1/60th of a second
 by default),
 if this is the active state.

defs.name: update
defs.value: fn (&mut self, _data: StateData<'_, T>) -> Trans<T, E>
defs.docs:
Executed on every frame immediately, as fast as the engine will allow (taking into account the frame rate limit),
 if this is the active state.

defs.name: shadow_fixed_update
defs.docs:
Executed repeatedly at stable, predictable intervals (1/60th of a second
 by default),
 even when this is not the active state,
 as long as this state is on the [StateMachine](struct.StateMachine.html)'s state-stack.

defs.name: shadow_update
defs.docs:
Executed on every frame immediately, as fast as the engine will allow (taking into account the frame rate limit),
 even when this is not the active state,
 as long as this state is on the [StateMachine](struct.StateMachine.html)'s state-stack.

defs.name: transition
defs.value: fn (&mut self, request: Trans<T, E>, data: StateData<'_, T>) -> ()
defs.docs:
Performs a state transition.
 Usually called by update or fixed_update by the user's defined `State`.
 This method can also be called when there are one or multiple `Trans` stored in the
 global `EventChannel<TransEvent<T, E>>`. Such `Trans` will be passed to this method
 sequentially in the order of insertion.
